## What happened

**`DSA.Create()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on macOS** because Apple removed DSA support from its native security frameworks (Security.framework / CommonCrypto). .NET's macOS crypto provider relies on those frameworks, so once the compatibility shim or fallback was removed in .NET 11, `DSA.Create()` fails at runtime.

This isn't new — DSA on macOS has been on a deprecation path for several .NET releases. Linux (via OpenSSL) and Windows (via CNG/CAPI) still support it.

## How to fix it

You have a few options, depending on your constraints:

### Option 1: Use a managed crypto library (recommended)
Use **BouncyCastle** (`Portable.BouncyCastle` or `BouncyCastle.Cryptography`), which implements DSA entirely in managed code — no OS dependency:

```csharp
// dotnet add package BouncyCastle.Cryptography
using Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Parameters;
using Org.BouncyCastle.Security;

var verifier = SignerUtilities.GetSigner("SHA256withDSA");
verifier.Init(false, publicKeyParams);
verifier.BlockUpdate(data, 0, data.Length);
bool valid = verifier.VerifySignature(signature);
```

### Option 2: Guard with a runtime check
If you can tolerate skipping DSA on macOS:

```csharp
if (!OperatingSystem.IsMacOS())
{
    using var dsa = DSA.Create();
    // verify signature
}
```

### Option 3: Bring your own OpenSSL on macOS
Install OpenSSL via Homebrew (`brew install openssl`) and set `DOTNET_SYSTEM_SECURITY_CRYPTOGRAPHY_OPENSSL` or use a custom P/Invoke wrapper — but this adds a deployment dependency.

**Recommendation:** If you must verify legacy DSA signatures cross-platform, go with **Option 1** (BouncyCastle). It's the only approach that works everywhere without OS-level dependencies.
